//
// Troubleshooting guide for PlasmaZones end-users.  Content
// sourced from the repo README (Troubleshooting section) plus
// scripts/build-docs.sh + configdefaults.h for file paths.

import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Topbar from "../../components/Topbar.astro";
import { Code } from "astro-expressive-code/components";
import PageHero from "../../components/PageHero.astro";
import SiteFooter from "../../components/SiteFooter.astro";
import Breadcrumb from "../../components/Breadcrumb.astro";
import GuideToc from "../../components/GuideToc.astro";
import { extractGuideHeadings } from "../../lib/toc";
import "../../styles/home.css";
import "../../styles/guide.css";

const toc = extractGuideHeadings(import.meta.url);
---

<BaseLayout
    title="Troubleshooting — PlasmaZones"
    description="Fix common PlasmaZones issues: daemon not starting, zones not appearing, KCM cache, verbose logging, support reports."
>
    <Topbar crumb="Troubleshooting" current="plasmazones" />

    <main id="main" class="container guide">

        <Breadcrumb href="/plasmazones/" label="PlasmaZones" />

        <PageHero
            title="Troubleshooting"
            tagline="First things to check when PlasmaZones misbehaves."
        >
            <p class="muted">
                If something below doesn't resolve the issue, attach a
                <a href="#support-report">support report</a> to your
                bug on
                <a href="https://github.com/fuddlesworth/PlasmaZones/issues">GitHub Issues</a>.
                It bundles config, layouts, screen topology, and
                recent daemon logs with home paths redacted.
            </p>
        </PageHero>

        <GuideToc entries={toc} />

        <h2 id="kcm">PlasmaZones not appearing in System Settings (KDE only)</h2>
        <p>
            KDE caches installed KCM modules. After a source install,
            the cache needs a rebuild before the new module shows up
            under <b>System Settings › Window Management</b>.
        </p>
        <Code lang="bash" code={`kbuildsycoca6 --noincremental`} />
        <p class="muted">
            Logging out and back in triggers the same rebuild. The
            standalone settings app doesn't depend on the cache and
            is always available via <code>plasmazones-settings</code>.
        </p>

        <h2 id="daemon">Daemon not starting</h2>
        <p>
            PlasmaZones runs as a systemd user service
            (<code>plasmazones.service</code>). The usual trio covers
            most cases:
        </p>
        <Code lang="bash" code={`# Current status + last few log lines
systemctl --user status plasmazones.service

# Tail the full journal (Ctrl-C to stop)
journalctl --user -u plasmazones.service -f

# Restart after a config change or upgrade
systemctl --user restart plasmazones.service`} />
        <p class="muted">
            If the service is reporting <code>inactive (dead)</code>
            and nothing obvious stands out in the journal, move on to
            <a href="#logs">verbose logging</a> to surface category
            breadcrumbs.
        </p>

        <h2 id="logs">Capturing verbose logs</h2>
        <p>
            <code>--debug</code> turns on every
            <code>plasmazones.*</code> logging category at once;
            <code>--log-file</code> redirects output away from the
            journal so a single run is easy to attach to an issue.
        </p>
        <Code lang="bash" code={`# Stop the service so it doesn't race with the manual run
systemctl --user stop plasmazones.service

# Run the daemon in the foreground with full logs
plasmazonesd --debug --log-file /tmp/pz.log

# ... reproduce the issue, then Ctrl-C, then:
systemctl --user start plasmazones.service`} />
        <p class="muted">
            The log file is plain text; <code>grep</code> by category
            (e.g. <code>grep 'plasmazones.snapping' /tmp/pz.log</code>)
            narrows it to a single subsystem.
        </p>

        <h2 id="no-zones">Zones not appearing when dragging</h2>
        <p>
            Four things to rule out, in order of frequency:
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                The daemon isn't running. Check with
                <code>systemctl --user status plasmazones.service</code>
                and start it if it isn't active.
            </li>
            <li>
                The drag modifier doesn't match. Default is
                <code>Alt</code>; the
                <a href="/plasmazones/shortcuts/#drag">shortcuts
                reference</a> lists the other configurable options
                (Meta, Ctrl+Alt, Alt+Shift, Alt+Meta, Ctrl+Alt+Meta).
                Check <b>Settings › Snapping › Activation</b>.
            </li>
            <li>
                The current layout has no zones. Open
                <code>Meta+Shift+E</code> to confirm; a layout with
                zero zones skips the overlay.
            </li>
            <li>
                The application is excluded. Apps on the exclusion
                list (<b>Settings › Exclusions</b>) never trigger
                snapping, which is useful for dialogs and
                media-player popups but occasionally catches a
                window by surprise.
            </li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="min-size">Tiles not reaching their intended size</h2>
        <p>
            Some apps (Firefox, Chromium-based apps, a handful of
            Electron apps) enforce a minimum size that prevents
            PlasmaZones from tiling them at the target geometry.
            The fix lives in KWin, not PlasmaZones:
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <b>System Settings › Window Management › Window
                Rules</b>.
            </li>
            <li>
                Add a rule matching the window class (use the
                picker — the eyedropper tool — to grab it from the
                misbehaving window).
            </li>
            <li>
                Under the <b>Size &amp; Position</b> tab, set
                <b>Minimum Size</b> to <b>Force</b>
                <code>0×0</code>.
            </li>
        </ol>
        <p class="muted">
            Forcing <code>0×0</code> removes the app's minimum-size
            constraint for KWin; PlasmaZones can then tile the
            window at whatever size the layout asks for.
        </p>

        <h2 id="support-report">Generating a support report</h2>
        <p>
            When filing a bug, attach a support report. It bundles:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Your <code>~/.config/plasmazones/config.json</code></li>
            <li>All layouts under <code>~/.local/share/plasmazones/layouts/</code></li>
            <li>Current screen topology (monitor geometry + virtual-screen splits)</li>
            <li>Recent daemon logs (default 30 min, configurable)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Home paths are redacted so you can attach reports publicly.</p>
        <Code lang="bash" code={`# Default: 30 minutes of logs, archive written to /tmp
plasmazones-report

# 60 minutes of logs (max 120)
plasmazones-report --since 60

# Write to a specific directory
plasmazones-report --output ~/Desktop`} />
        <p>Or trigger the same collection over D-Bus:</p>
        <Code lang="bash" code={`qdbus6 org.plasmazones /PlasmaZones \\
  org.plasmazones.Control.generateSupportReport 0`} />
        <p class="muted">
            The D-Bus path is what the
            <code>plasmazones-report</code> CLI uses internally, and
            what scripting integrations should prefer. See the
            <a href="/plasmazones/dbus/">D-Bus API reference</a>
            for the full surface.
        </p>

        <h2 id="next">Still stuck?</h2>
        <ul class="links">
            <li>
                <a href="https://github.com/fuddlesworth/PlasmaZones/issues">GitHub Issues →</a>
                <span class="muted">Attach a support report from above and describe what you expected vs. what happened.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="/plasmazones/shortcuts/">Keyboard shortcuts →</a>
                <span class="muted">Every default binding and where to rebind it.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="/plasmazones/getting-started/">First-run tour →</a>
                <span class="muted">Verify the install, open the editor, snap a window.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="/plasmazones/dbus/">D-Bus scripting →</a>
                <span class="muted">Inspect daemon state and drive it from scripts.</span>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <SiteFooter rightHref="/plasmazones/" rightLabel="Back to PlasmaZones" />

    </main>
</BaseLayout>
